Case Studies

Da (Harry) Lu

1 Analysis

1.1 Question

Background

We have websites that offer real estate and credit information to consumers on a monthly subscription basis, offered as a 7-day trial first. We don’t get much revenue from the trial (which is typically just $1) but rather, we get most of our revenue from the monthly recurring subscription fee a customer pays after the trial (which is typically $49).

To generate revenue, we partner with marketing companies to send us visitors to our sites. If a visitor becomes a “sale” (meaning he signs up for a 7 day trial on our site), we pay a commission to the marketing partner.

We are constantly testing new pages on the sites and want to assess performance of the new pages to try and optimize profitability of the overall business. We tested new versions of the site on different traffic sources (Traffic1 - Email, Traffic2 - Display, Traffic3 - Search) where our old version (control) was put head to head in an AB test against the new version (challenger). The traffic was split evenly between control and challenger.

Analyze the test results below and present findings, giving a recommendation about what we should do for the traffic that is being tested.

Definitions

  • Visitors are unique people who view our site
  • Sales are people who sign up for our 7 day trial subscription service
  • M1 are people who stay for the full 7 days and we have collected money for the monthly charge
  • C1 are people who cancel within the 7 days and we will not collect any more money
  • D1 are people who stay for the full 7 days and we are unable to collect money for the monthly charge. We will try again to collect money from these people.
  • LTV is an estimated lifetime revenue for each sale based off the money we have already collected
  • CPA is the amount we pay out to our marketing partner for each sale
. . visitors sales M1 C1 D1 LTV CPA
Traffic 1 (Email) Control 1 21643 470 143 130 197 57.9 35
. Challenger 1 21729 557 160 132 265 55.7 35
Traffic 2 (Display) Control 2 11419 372 117 102 153 60 40
. Challenger 2 11452 400 130 97 173 62.9 40
Traffic 3 (Search) Control 3 26113 207 73 65 69 65 45
. Challenger 3 26338 250 90 56 104 68.5 45

1.2 Answer

library(knitr)
traffic_sources = c("Email", "Email", "Display", "Display", "Search", "Search")
versions = c("Control", "Challenger", "Control", "Challenger", "Control", "Challenger")
visitors = c(21643, 21729, 11419, 11452, 26113, 26338)
sales = c(470, 557, 372, 400, 207, 250)
M1 = c(143, 160, 117, 130, 73, 90)
C1 = c(130, 132, 102, 97, 65, 56)
D1 = c(197, 265, 153, 173, 69, 104)
LTV = c(57.9, 55.7, 60, 62.9, 65, 68.5)
CPA = c(35, 35, 40, 40, 45, 45)
t = data.frame(traffic_sources, versions, visitors, sales, M1, C1, D1, LTV, CPA)
kable(t)
traffic_sources versions visitors sales M1 C1 D1 LTV CPA
Email Control 21643 470 143 130 197 57.9 35
Email Challenger 21729 557 160 132 265 55.7 35
Display Control 11419 372 117 102 153 60.0 40
Display Challenger 11452 400 130 97 173 62.9 40
Search Control 26113 207 73 65 69 65.0 45
Search Challenger 26338 250 90 56 104 68.5 45
  • M_S: Ratio of “M1” to “sales”. The conversion rate among the sales.
  • C_S: Ratio of “C1” to “sales”.
  • D_S: Ratio of “D1” to “sales”. The potential rate that we need to focus, because this ratio is our potential customers and it may convert to “M1” to bring us more income.
  • M_V: Ratio of “M1” to “visitors”. The conversion rate among the visitors.
  • C_V: Ratio of “C1” to “visitors”.
  • D_V: Ratio of “D1” to “visitors”.
  • SIN_RVN: The difference between LTV and CPA on a single sale.
library(scales)
t$M_S = percent(t$M1 / t$sales)
t$C_S = percent(t$C1 / t$sales)
t$D_S = percent(t$D1 / t$sales)
t$M_V = percent(t$M1 / t$visitors)
t$C_V = percent(t$C1 / t$visitors)
t$D_V = percent(t$D1 / t$visitors)
t$SIN_RVN = t$LTV - t$CPA
kable(t)

2 Technical

2.1 Part 1

2.1.1 Question

Background

For some of our internal reports, we query the database directly using SQL. Below is the query that pulls data for a “Downsell” report.

Please explain:

  • What data this report will show including any conditions
  • How this report actually looks like (just make up data as necessary)
  • List what database tables are sources for this report
  • How database tables in this query are connected

Definitions

  • Downsell - when a user is cancelling their subscription with us (i.e. leaving us as a customer), we try to generate additional revenue by offering a discounted product at a lower price. Since our regular product is a nationwide service for $49 per month, we offer a single-state product (e.g. California only) for only $5 per month
  • id_brand - this is a unique numeric identifier for a given website we own
  • order_date - the date the user signed up for our service i.e. when the order was created
  • signup_type - the type of product that the user signed up for. Our regular product is a “recurring” signup type, while the downsell is a “downsell” sign up type
  • test_account - key that defines if the order is a test signup i.e. done internally by our employees or our robots. It equals 1 for test orders and 0 for real orders
SELECT
  DATE(nic_billing.order.order_date) AS date,
  count(nic_billing.order.order_date) AS downsells,
  count(if(nic_billing.order.id_brand = 1,nic_billing.order.order_date,NULL)) AS downsells_1,
  count(if(nic_billing.order.id_brand = 2,nic_billing.order.order_date,NULL)) AS downsells_2,
  count(if(nic_billing.order.id_brand = 3,nic_billing.order.order_date,NULL)) AS downsells_3,
  count(if(nic_billing.order.id_brand = 4,nic_billing.order.order_date,NULL)) AS downsells_4,
  count(if(nic_billing.order.id_brand = 5,nic_billing.order.order_date,NULL)) AS downsells_5,
  count(if(nic_billing.order.id_brand = 6,nic_billing.order.order_date,NULL)) AS downsells_6
FROM
  nic_billing.membership
  LEFT JOIN nic_billing.order_item
    ON nic_billing.order_item.id_membership = nic_billing.membership.id_membership
  LEFT JOIN nic_billing.order
    ON nic_billing.order.id_order = nic_billing.order_item.id_order
  LEFT JOIN nic_offer.offer
    ON nic_offer.offer.id_offer = nic_billing.order_item.id_offer
  INNER JOIN main.tbl_customer
    ON main.tbl_customer.CUSTOMER_ID = nic_billing.membership.id_customer
WHERE
  nic_billing.order.order_status = 'success' AND
  nic_offer.offer.signup_type = 'downsell' AND
  nic_billing.order.order_date > ADDDATE(CURRENT_DATE,INTERVAL -14 DAY) AND
  main.tbl_customer.test_account <> 1
GROUP BY
  DAY(nic_billing.order.order_date)
ORDER BY
  DAY(nic_billing.order.order_date) DESC

I assume that the id_brand only has six values, from 1 to 6. Then downsells should be the sum of downsells_1 to downsells_6.

3 Business

3.1 Question

We are selling our product on subscription basis. Our customers pay a monthly membership fee, after a $1 trial for 7 days.

One of the challenges of a subscription business is to forecast the subscription revenue we collect from each customer (also known as the LTV, or Lifetime Value that was referenced in the Case 1). On one hand, it’s necessary to know the LTV because we need that value to know if the business is profitable. For instance, it the LTV is $100 but we are paying $120 to acquire each customer, that is clearly not a profitable business to pursue. On the other hand, it is very difficult to know what the LTV is when you first acquire the customer, since it may take many months for the revenue to come in, as we charge the customer each month they remain a member subscribed to our product. For instance, if the customer cancels their membership on the same day they signed up, then the LTV for that customer is only $1. But if a different customer remains subscribed for 2 months after signing up, then the LTV for that customer would be $81 (assuming we charge the customer $40 per month). That’s a big difference in LTV for those 2 customers!

Within Nations Info, it is the responsibility of the BI Team to forecast the LTV. We are using cohort approach to forecast LTV. For this exercise, we will define the cohort as the group of customers that sign up in a given month (e.g. January). We will need to calculate the revenue we get from this January cohort in the subsequent months (February, March, April, etc). We call that sequence of revenue a “Revenue Tail” - see chart below. This chart shows the % of the initial cohort that gets charged each month after they signed up. We use the notation “M1” to mean the % that got billed for month 1, “M2” to mean the % that got billed for month 2, and so on. In the example chart below, if you assume that the cohort consisted of 100 initial customers, then 40 people paid us the membership fee in M1 and only 20 people paid us in M2 and 14 paid us in M3, and so on.

The M1% metric is the leading indicator of the cohort’s LTV, since all future charges (M2%, M3%, etc) are a function of how big (or small) M1% is. To state the obvious, the cohort with M1% = 40% almost always has a higher LTV than a cohort with M1% = 30%

Questions

1. Our Marketing Manager has asked you to forecast the LTV for a new source of customers “Partner X”. Here is all of the information that we know about these customers:

  • M1% = 41.5%
  • Membership fee we are charging these customers is $40 per month, after a 7-day trial
  • Retention tail for partners that are similar to Partner X have a Retention Tail that looks like the following table:
M1 M2 M3 M4 M5 M6 M7 M8 M9 M10 M11 M12
38.17% 18.76% 12.12% 9.06% 6.49% 4.65% 3.65% 2.78% 2.39% 2.16% 1.74% 1.56%

Could you forecast LTV for partner X?

2. Partner X offers us two options:

  • 1000 sales with CPA (cost per acquisition) = $40 or
  • 2000 sales with CPA = $42.

What option will you recommend the Marketing Team choose?

4 Metrics Definition (Bonus)

4.1 Question

One responsibility of BI analyst is to co-work with different business units and understand their day-to-day operation. Then the analyst will collect business needs from the owner of business unit and define the metrics for the owner so as to make it easier to monitor the healthiness of business and drill into different granularities when abnormality is detected. The business owners may not necessarily understand data structure or anything in database, so it’s important to translate business needs into trackable and queryable code.

The important part of our business is to make sure we have enough listings of properties to show to our customers. For example, when you are searching for a house on our website, and you type in your zip code, then you will be re-directed to another web page which lists all the properties close to that zip code. Every day we have thousands of customers launching different searches, so it is important to make sure we have enough “supplies” of property listings on each of their search request.

Suppose you are now working with our manager who is in charge of property listings. He invites engineering team to tell you that:

  1. We are currently collecting listings from different data sources. Each data source has a unique id assigned to it.
  2. For each data source, we are compiling the data we collect into one single table called tbl_mapped (data schema is below, sample data is attached separately)
  3. Since different data sources may contain the same properties, we will then merge the same properties in tbl_mapped and store the data in tbl_merged so that each row of the table will be a unique record of property and will not overlap with the information of other rows.
  4. Finally we will combine the information in tbl_merged with our old listings and store them in tbl_prop, which is the actual listing shown to our customers.

Table 1: tbl_mapped

Field Name Type Description
mapped_id Int The primary key in the table
Date Datetime When the property is imported into our database
Data source Int An index assigned to each data source, this id is common in each table.
Address Text A string illustrating the specific address of a property
Zip Int The zip code of the property
City Text The city where the property is located
State State The state where the property is located
Sale_type Text How the property is sold, for example, through auction, pre-foreclosure, etc.

Table 2: tbl_merged

Field Name Type Description
merged_id Int The primary key in the table, it is different from primary keys above.
Date Datetime When the property is imported into our database
Data sources Text A combination of indices assigned to each data sources ([2715,2019] means that the property comes from data source 2715 and 2019 stored in tables above)
Address Text A string illustrating the specific address of a property
Zip Int The zip code of the property
City Text The city where the property is located
State State The state where the property is located
Sale_type Text How the property is sold, for example, through auction, pre-foreclosure, etc.
Property_id Int A unique index assigned to each property

Table 3: tbl_prop

Field Name Type Description
Property_id Int A unique index assigned to each property, it is the same id used in tbl_merged
Date Datetime When the property is imported into our database
Data sources Text A combination of indices assigned to each data sources ([2715,2019] means that the property comes from data source 2715 and 2019 stored in tables above)
Address Text A string illustrating the specific address of a property
Zip Int The zip code of the property
City Text The city where the property is located
State State The state where the property is located
Sale_type Text How the property is sold, for example, through auction, pre-foreclosure, etc.
Contact Text The contact information of that property, it might be null in some rows
Picture URL Text The URL that displays the picture of that property, it might be null in some rows
Price Int The price of that property which is rounded to the nearest integer.

Based on the work flow and data schema, our manager is asking you to design key metrics for:

  1. Listings monitoring to make sure we have enough listings for customers with different demands
  2. Comparison of the data quality and property quality of different data sources (it’s important because we are paying for those data.) In other words, the manager wants to know whether the property provided by different data sources is as valuable as each other.

To complete this task:

  1. What additional questions will you ask, or what additional information will you need?
  2. What metrics will you suggest to use? What information do those metrics reflect? Why do you think the metrics are important?
  3. How would you generate a report in database (the general methodology, please use descriptive language to describe what you plan to do step by step)? For example, step 1. create table A which shows information from…; step 2. create another table from A to show…
  4. Provide a SQL sample to create the report you mentioned in Q3 (if you find some code requiring time to recall or learn, just leave a note explaining what function is to be realized by the code)
